# Mendly - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
Mendly is a mobile-first AI-powered life management app built with React Native + Expo, Supabase backend, and OpenAI integration. Target users: ADHD-type individuals with multiple goals and limited planning time.

---

## 🎯 Core Principles

### 1. Design-First Development
- NEVER implement features without a design doc in `docs/02-design/features/{feature}.design.md`
- Design docs MUST include: API contracts, data models, component tree, error handling, security considerations
- Implementation MUST match design; deviations require design doc updates

### 2. Type Safety & Validation
- Strict TypeScript: NO `any`, `@ts-ignore`, or loose types
- Zod schemas for ALL API inputs/outputs, form data, and AI responses
- Runtime validation at system boundaries (API routes, form submissions, AI responses)
- Supabase types generated from schema: `npx supabase gen types typescript`

### 3. AI Integration Standards
- ALL AI calls wrapped in try-catch with fallback behavior
- Structured outputs via JSON mode or Zod schema validation
- Cost tracking: log token usage and provider for every AI call
- Rate limiting on AI endpoints (10 req/min free, 50 req/min pro)
- Never expose raw AI errors to users; translate to human-friendly messages

### 4. Mobile-First UX
- Touch targets ≥44×44dp (iOS), ≥48×48dp (Android)
- Gesture-friendly: swipe-to-delete, pull-to-refresh, pan gestures
- Offline-first: queue actions when offline, sync when online
- Loading states on ALL async actions (skeleton screens, spinners, progress bars)
- Error states with retry actions
- Empty states with clear CTAs

### 5. Critical Thinking (see .cursor/rules/critical-thinking.mdc)
- Before implementing: check preconditions, alternatives, and side effects of the user's request.
- Vague wording ("이쁘게", "편하게") → translate to 1–2 concrete specs and get user choice before coding.
- Conditional requests ("지금이 더 낫다면 냅둬도 됨") → state comparison criteria and recommend "keep" vs "change" with reasons.

